167.text: Biochemist Paul Berg at Stanford University in California , who organized the Asilomar conference

142.text: Marcy Darnovsky , director of the Center for Genetics and Society in Berkeley , California

81.text: Jennifer Doudna , a biochemist at the University of California , Berkeley , and an inventor of the CRISPR technique , who has called for more discussion on the ethics of editing the human genome

quotes.text: " I am delighted that the NAS and the NAM are leading a discussion of these important issues,"
quotes.speaker: Jennifer Doudna

quotes.text: "This is indeed the kind of response we hoped to trigger,"
quotes.speaker: Jennifer Doudna

quotes.text: "Whether a larger or more public forum is needed depends on how the initiative proceeds."
quotes.speaker: Ralph Cicerone

quotes.text: "really more international than Asilomar ever had to be,"
quotes.speaker: Cicerone

quotes.text: "It was an effort at fending off any sort of binding policy in favour of self-regulation."
quotes.speaker: Marcy Darnovsky

quotes.text: "The idea is to get the idea out, and to get it out by a highly focused conference with the expectation that this is going to resound much louder and wider,"
quotes.speaker: Paul Berg

quotes.text: "Then there will be different ways of dealing with those [ideas]."
quotes.speaker: Unknown
